    <stitle>FRONT AXLES: INTERNATIONAL BY SPICER I-BEAM - KING PIN BUSHING REPLACEMENT</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>KING PIN BUSHING REPLACEMENT</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="4">
            <title>STEERING KNUCKLE REMOVAL</title>
            <para>The following procedure applies to one knuckle, repeat the procedure for the remaining knuckle.</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Block rear wheels.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Raise the vehicle. Support vehicle on stands; each stand by the spring pad area of the
                    axle.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove wheels. Refer to GROUP 17 - WHEELS, RIMS AND TIRES Section in the CTS-5000 Master
                    Service Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove brake assembly from knuckle. Refer to GROUP 04 - BRAKES in the CTS-5000 Master
                    Service Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove tie rod assembly and drag link from steering arms. If necessary, remove steering
                    arms from knuckle. Refer to GROUP 05 - STEERING in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove draw key.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Staked draw keys: drive the staked draw key out at the opposite end of staking using
                        a drift and brass hammer (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0200406">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0200406" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0200406" filename="../figg02/g0200406.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                                 scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6. Removing Draw Key</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Threaded draw keys: remove nut and Belleville washers. Strike the threaded end of
                        draw key with drift and brass hammer.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Medium and heavy-duty axles all use dual draw keys. Medium duty axle codes 02ADA and
                                02ADB use staked draw keys. Heavy-duty axle codes 02ADC, 02ADD, 02ADE and 02ADG have
                                threaded draw keys (
                                <hotlnk xrefid="f0200407">Figure 7</hotlnk>).
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="f0200407" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0200407" filename="../figg02/g0200407.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                                 scalefitwidth="192px" scalefitheight="152px" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7. Draw Keys</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. STAKED DRAW KEY</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. THREADED DRAW KEY</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove top and bottom steering knuckle caps (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200408">Figure 8</hotlnk>). If there are O-rings under the caps, they must be
                    removed.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200408" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0200408" filename="../figg02/g0200408.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 8. Removing or Installing Steering Knuckle Cap</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drive out the king pin using a brass drift punch and hammer (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200409">Figure 9</hotlnk>). If the king pin is difficult to remove, a hydraulic
                    press can be used. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s02004t_13.xml" xrefid="hl0200401">SPECIAL TOOLS</hotlnk>.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200409" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0200409" filename="../figg02/g0200409.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 9. Removing King Pin</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Draw key must be removed prior to king pin removal.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove steering knuckles, thrust bearings and any spacer shims present. Keep spacer
                    shim(s) together.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Thoroughly clean all parts and dry.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
